</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Although the vast majority of gastrointestinal (GI) masses are epithelial neoplasms, a variety of subepithelial masses are infrequently encountered during endoscopic or radiologic examination. A subepithelial mass, which was previously called a submucosal mass, is defined as a mass covered with normal-appearing mucosa, whether the underlying process is intramural or extramural in origin. At contrast material–enhanced computed tomography (CT), hypervascular subepithelial masses are usually detected more easily than isoattenuating or hypovascular masses. Entities that appear as intramural hypervascular subepithelial lesions include neuroendocrine tumors, GI stromal tumor, glomus tumor, hemangioma, angiosarcoma, Kaposi sarcoma, nerve sheath tumors, hypervascular metastases, heterotopic tissues, and vascular structures. Entities that appear as extramural hypervascular subepithelial lesions include Castleman disease, solitary fibrous tumor, inflammatory myofibroblastic tumor, and actinomycosis. Some rare gastric cancers resemble subepithelial tumors. In comparison with endoscopic ultrasonography, CT is of limited value in differentiating the layers of the GI wall and determining the origin of mass lesions. However, recent advances in multidetector CT with multiplanar reformation allow one to determine whether a GI mass is of epithelial, intramural subepithelial, or extramural subepithelial origin. Furthermore, the full extent of tumors can be delineated, and local invasion and distant metastases can be identified. Familiarity with the characteristic CT appearances of hypervascular subepithelial masses of the GI tract will help radiologists make a more confident diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2010</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.307105028">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.307105028">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig01a.jpeg" height="1541" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig01a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig01b.jpeg" height="1546" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig01b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig01c.jpeg" height="1541" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig01c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig02a.jpeg" height="1502" width="1728" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig02a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig02b.jpeg" height="1560" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig02b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig02c.jpeg" height="1385" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig02c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig03.jpeg" height="614" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig03" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Growth patterns of intramural subepithelial masses. Intramural subepithelial masses tend to grow in an intraluminal <i>(A)</i>, extraluminal <i>(B)</i>, or mixed (dumbbell-shaped) <i>(C)</i> pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig03">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig04.jpeg" height="1494" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig04" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Well-differentiated neuroendocrine tumor of the small bowel in a 66-year-old man. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows an 8-mm intraluminal enhancing mass (arrow) in the terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig04">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig05a.jpeg" height="1426" width="1458" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig05b.jpeg" height="1444" width="1476" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig05c.jpeg" height="1092" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig05c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig06.jpeg" height="1217" width="1404" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Poorly differentiated neuroendocrine carcinoma of the stomach with liver metastases in a 52-year-old woman. Contrast-enhanced CT image obtained during the late arterial phase shows an infiltrative mass with heterogeneous enhancement (black arrows) in the lesser curvature of the gastric body, findings that mimic those of advanced gastric carcinoma. Note the multiple liver metastases with peripheral rim enhancement (arrowheads) and the metastatic lymphadenopathy (white arrow) in the left gastric area.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig07.jpeg" height="1602" width="1513" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Well-differentiated neuroendocrine tumor of the small bowel in a 66-year-old man. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows a spiculated mesenteric mass (arrow) with a small amount of calcification. Note the concentric mural thickening with suboptimal enhancement (arrowheads) of the adjacent small bowel loop, a finding due to proved ischemia. (Courtesy of J. Y. Oh, MD, Dong-A University Hospital, Busan, Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig08a.jpeg" height="1500" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig08a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig08b.jpeg" height="1504" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig09.jpeg" height="1530" width="1530" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Well-differentiated neuroendocrine tumor of the rectum in a 54-year-old man. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 1.7-cm, well-defined hypervascular intraluminal mass (arrow) in the rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig10a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig10b.jpeg" height="1620" width="1620" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig11.jpeg" height="1620" width="1620" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> GIST of the jejunum with intussusception in a 62-year-old woman. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows a jejunojejunal intussusception secondary to a 1.5-cm, well-defined, homogeneously enhancing, polypoid mass (arrow) in the jejunum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig12.jpeg" height="1380" width="1656" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Malignant GIST of the stomach with a liver metastasis in a 59-year-old man. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows a large, lobulated, exophytic mass (arrows) with heterogeneous enhancement and central necrosis in the greater curvature of the gastric body. Note the liver metastasis (arrowhead) with central necrosis and a peripherally enhancing portion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig13a.jpeg" height="1566" width="1566" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig13b.jpeg" height="1530" width="1530" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig14.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Hemangioma of the rectum in a 38-year-old woman. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows homogeneously enhanced transmural bowel wall thickening containing phleboliths (arrow) along with phleboliths in the perirectal space (arrowheads). (Courtesy of J. H. Cho, MD, Dong-A University Hospital, Busan, Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig15a.jpeg" height="1653" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig15b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig16a.jpeg" height="1480" width="1638" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig16b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig17a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig17b.jpeg" height="1710" width="1710" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig18a.jpeg" height="1320" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig18b.jpeg" height="939" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig19a.jpeg" height="1656" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig19b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig20.jpeg" height="1440" width="1440" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 20</span> Heterotopic pancreas of the stomach in a 47-year-old woman. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 3-cm, ill-defined, ovoid intraluminal subepithelial mass (arrow) in the gastric antrum. The lesion has homogeneous enhancement similar to that of the pancreas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig21.jpeg" height="1458" width="1458" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Heterotopic pancreas of the jejunum in a 46-year-old woman. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 2.8-cm, ill-defined, lobulated mass (arrow) in the jejunum. The mass demonstrates enhancement similar to that of the orthotopic pancreas (*). The ascites in the peritoneal cavity is due to recent surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig22.jpeg" height="1458" width="1458" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Heterotopic gastric tissue in a Meckel diverticulum in a 20-year-old man. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a 2-cm, well-defined, hypervascular intraluminal masslike lesion (arrows) in a blind-ending tubular structure (*). Pathologic analysis demonstrated heterotopic gastric tissue in a Meckel diverticulum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig23.jpeg" height="1476" width="1476" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Duodenal varices in a 62-year-old man with occult GI bleeding. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows varices (arrows) in the posterior wall of the third part of the duodenum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig24.jpeg" height="1620" width="1620" aria-labelledby="fig24" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24</span> Castleman disease (hyaline vascular type) in a 49-year-old woman. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-defined, homogeneously enhancing mass (arrow) abutting the duodenum. Note the preservation of the fat plane between the mass and the duodenum, a finding indicative of an extramural subepithelial mass. (Courtesy of J. H. Cho, MD, Dong-A University Hospital, Busan, Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig24">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig25.jpeg" height="1620" width="1620" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> SFT of the perineum in a 67-year-old woman. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a well-circumscribed, lobulated, large heterogeneous mass (arrows) with avid enhancement abutting and displacing the rectum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig26.jpeg" height="1656" width="1656" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Inflammatory myofibroblastic tumor in a 48-year-old woman. Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a slightly lobulated, homogeneously enhancing mass (arrows) in the right paracolic gutter. Abdominal wall invasion by the mass is suspected. (Courtesy of S. H. Kim, MD, Daegu Fatima Hospital, Daegu, Korea.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig27a.jpeg" height="1335" width="1476" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.307105028/asset/images/105028fig27b.jpeg" height="1280" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.307105028&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hwang JH, Kimmey MB. The incidental upper gastrointestinal subepithelial mass. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2004;126(1):301–307.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2003.11.040">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14699508/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+incidental+upper+gastrointestinal+subepithelial+mass&amp;author=JH+Hwang&amp;author=MB+Kimmey&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Gastroenterology&amp;pages=301-307&amp;doi=10.1053%2Fj.gastro.2003.11.040&amp;pmid=14699508">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Humphris JL, Jones DB. Subepithelial mass lesions in the upper gastrointestinal tract. <em>J Gastroenterol Hepatol</em> 2008;23(4):556–566.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1440-1746.2007.05232.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18086121/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Subepithelial+mass+lesions+in+the+upper+gastrointestinal+tract&amp;author=JL+Humphris&amp;author=DB+Jones&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=J+Gastroenterol+Hepatol&amp;pages=556-566&amp;doi=10.1111%2Fj.1440-1746.2007.05232.x&amp;pmid=18086121">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Ponsaing LG, Kiss K, Loft A, Jensen LI, Hansen MB. Diagnostic procedures for submucosal tumors in the gastrointestinal tract. <em>World J Gastroenterol</em> 2007;13(24):3301–3310.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.3748/wjg.v13.i24.3301">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17659668/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Diagnostic+procedures+for+submucosal+tumors+in+the+gastrointestinal+tract&amp;author=LG+Ponsaing&amp;author=K+Kiss&amp;author=A+Loft&amp;author=LI+Jensen&amp;author=MB+Hansen&amp;publication_year=200